questions.prompt:
Write an if/else if/else chain that assigns a grade label to a Publica Academy student based on their score. Use these bands: 80+ → 'Distinction', 70–79 → 'Merit', 60–69 → 'Credit', 50–59 → 'Pass', below 50 → 'Fail — retake required'. Test with score = 67.

```js
const studentName = "Ngozi Eze";
const score       = 67;
// write your if/else if/else chain here
```

questions.expected_answer:
const studentName = "Ngozi Eze";
const score       = 67;

if (score >= 80) {
  console.log(studentName + " — Distinction");
} else if (score >= 70) {
  console.log(studentName + " — Merit");
} else if (score >= 60) {
  console.log(studentName + " — Credit");   // 67 lands here
} else if (score >= 50) {
  console.log(studentName + " — Pass");
} else {
  console.log(studentName + " — Fail — retake required");
}
// Output: Ngozi Eze — Credit

// Key requirements: conditions ordered from highest to lowest (most specific first);
// else at the end as catch-all; correct threshold values

questions.prompt:
A Paystack webhook sends a payment status. Write a switch statement that handles four statuses: 'success' → log 'Payment confirmed — receipt sent'; 'pending' → log 'Awaiting bank confirmation'; 'failed' → log 'Payment failed — please retry'; 'reversed' → log 'Transaction reversed — funds returned'. Add a default that logs 'Unknown status: ' + status. Test with status = 'pending'.

```js
const status = "pending";
// write your switch statement here
```

questions.expected_answer:
const status = "pending";

switch (status) {
  case "success":
    console.log("Payment confirmed — receipt sent");
    break;
  case "pending":
    console.log("Awaiting bank confirmation");   // runs
    break;
  case "failed":
    console.log("Payment failed — please retry");
    break;
  case "reversed":
    console.log("Transaction reversed — funds returned");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Unknown status:", status);
}
// Output: Awaiting bank confirmation

// Key requirements: break after every case; default present; case labels use === matching

questions.prompt:
The following switch statement has a fall-through bug. Identify the problem, explain what fall-through means, then write the corrected version.

```js
const deliveryZone = "Lagos";

switch (deliveryZone) {
  case "Lagos":
    console.log("Same-day delivery available");
  case "Abuja":
    console.log("Next-day delivery");
    break;
  case "Kano":
    console.log("3-day delivery");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Delivery not available in this zone");
}
```

questions.expected_answer:
Bug: missing break after the 'Lagos' case.

Fall-through means: when a switch case has no break statement, JavaScript does not stop after that case — it continues executing the code in the next case automatically, regardless of whether that case's value matches. In this example, deliveryZone is 'Lagos', so the Lagos case matches. But because there is no break, execution falls through into the 'Abuja' case and runs that code too.

Actual (buggy) output:
  Same-day delivery available
  Next-day delivery

Expected output:
  Same-day delivery available

Corrected version:
switch (deliveryZone) {
  case "Lagos":
    console.log("Same-day delivery available");
    break;   // ← added
  case "Abuja":
    console.log("Next-day delivery");
    break;
  case "Kano":
    console.log("3-day delivery");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Delivery not available in this zone");
}

questions.prompt:
Rewrite the following if/else as a ternary operator. Then explain in a comment when you would NOT use a ternary and should stick with if/else.

```js
let membershipLabel;
const isPremium = true;

if (isPremium) {
  membershipLabel = "Premium Member";
} else {
  membershipLabel = "Free Member";
}
console.log(membershipLabel);
```

questions.expected_answer:
const isPremium      = true;
const membershipLabel = isPremium ? "Premium Member" : "Free Member";
console.log(membershipLabel);  // Premium Member

// Key improvements: let becomes const (ternary assigns immediately);
// four lines become one line

// When NOT to use ternary (comment):
// Do not use ternary when either branch requires multiple statements,
// complex logic, or when the condition is long and hard to read on one line.
// Also avoid nested ternaries — a chain like:
//   score >= 80 ? 'A' : score >= 70 ? 'B' : 'C'
// is harder to read and debug than an if/else if chain.

questions.prompt:
A Bolt driver must meet two conditions to receive a bonus: more than 200 trips completed AND an average rating above 4.5. They receive a consolation discount if they have completed more than 100 trips OR maintained a rating above 4.8 (but did not qualify for the full bonus). Write the if/else if/else chain for this logic. Test with trips = 250 and rating = 4.6.

```js
const driverName = "Emeka Okafor";
const trips      = 250;
const rating     = 4.6;
// write your conditional here
```

questions.expected_answer:
const driverName = "Emeka Okafor";
const trips      = 250;
const rating     = 4.6;

if (trips > 200 && rating > 4.5) {
  console.log(driverName + ": Full bonus earned");        // runs (250>200 AND 4.6>4.5)
} else if (trips > 100 || rating > 4.8) {
  console.log(driverName + ": Consolation discount earned");
} else {
  console.log(driverName + ": No bonus this period");
}
// Output: Emeka Okafor: Full bonus earned

// Key: && requires both; || requires at least one; else if only checks when first if was false

questions.prompt:
Write a switch statement that maps a Publica Academy module number to its topic name. Group cases: modules 1–3 map to 'Foundations', modules 4–6 map to 'Core JavaScript', modules 7–9 map to 'Functions & Arrays', and anything else maps to 'Advanced Topics'.

Note: switch can only match exact values — you will need to list each module number as a separate case.

```js
const moduleNumber = 5;
// write your switch here
```

questions.expected_answer:
const moduleNumber = 5;

switch (moduleNumber) {
  case 1:
  case 2:
  case 3:
    console.log("Module", moduleNumber, "— Foundations");
    break;
  case 4:
  case 5:
  case 6:
    console.log("Module", moduleNumber, "— Core JavaScript");  // runs
    break;
  case 7:
  case 8:
  case 9:
    console.log("Module", moduleNumber, "— Functions & Arrays");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Module", moduleNumber, "— Advanced Topics");
}
// Output: Module 5 — Core JavaScript

// Key: stacked empty cases share one code block and one break; this is intentional grouping

const a = [];    // [] — truthy (empty array is an object reference)
if (a) { console.log("a: truthy"); } else { console.log("a: falsy"); }
// Output: a: truthy

const b = {};    // {} — truthy (empty object is an object reference)
if (b) { console.log("b: truthy"); } else { console.log("b: falsy"); }
// Output: b: truthy

const c = "";   // "" — FALSY (empty string)
if (c) { console.log("c: truthy"); } else { console.log("c: falsy"); }
// Output: c: falsy

const d = 0;    // 0 — FALSY (zero)
if (d) { console.log("d: truthy"); } else { console.log("d: falsy"); }
// Output: d: falsy

const e = "0";  // "0" — truthy (non-empty string — the content is irrelevant)
if (e) { console.log("e: truthy"); } else { console.log("e: falsy"); }
// Output: e: truthy

const f = null; // null — FALSY
if (f) { console.log("f: truthy"); } else { console.log("f: falsy"); }
// Output: f: falsy

questions.prompt:
The following if/else if chain has its conditions in the wrong order. Identify the problem, explain which outputs are unreachable, and rewrite it in the correct order.

```js
const orderTotal = 85000;

if (orderTotal >= 10000) {
  console.log("Free delivery");
} else if (orderTotal >= 50000) {
  console.log("Free delivery + gift");
} else if (orderTotal >= 100000) {
  console.log("VIP treatment + free delivery + gift");
} else {
  console.log("Standard: ₦500 delivery fee");
}
```

questions.expected_answer:
Problem: conditions are ordered from least specific (10000) to most specific (100000). For orderTotal = 85000: the first condition (>= 10000) is true, so JavaScript stops there and prints 'Free delivery'. The 'Free delivery + gift' (>= 50000) and 'VIP treatment' (>= 100000) cases are unreachable for any value >= 10000.

Unreachable outputs:
- 'Free delivery + gift' — never runs because >= 10000 catches everything above 10000 first
- 'VIP treatment + free delivery + gift' — same reason

Corrected (most specific first):
if (orderTotal >= 100000) {
  console.log("VIP treatment + free delivery + gift");
} else if (orderTotal >= 50000) {
  console.log("Free delivery + gift");   // 85000 lands here correctly
} else if (orderTotal >= 10000) {
  console.log("Free delivery");
} else {
  console.log("Standard: ₦500 delivery fee");
}
// Output: Free delivery + gift

